  <p><code>ProviderScope</code> holds the state for all providers in the subtree. It also enables easy testing through provider overrides:</p>
  <Code code={riverpodScopeCode} lang="dart" />

  <h3>Parameterized Providers (.family)</h3>
  <p>The <code>.family</code> modifier creates parameterized providers, useful for entity-specific state:</p>
  <Code code={riverpodFamilyCode} lang="dart" />

  <h3>Core Provider Types</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><code>Provider&lt;T&gt;</code> &mdash; immutable computed/derived values</li>
    <li><code>NotifierProvider&lt;T&gt;</code> &mdash; mutable state via Notifier class</li>
    <li><code>FutureProvider&lt;T&gt;</code> &mdash; async operations</li>
    <li><code>StreamProvider&lt;T&gt;</code> &mdash; stream-based values</li>
    <li><code>AsyncNotifierProvider&lt;T&gt;</code> &mdash; async mutable state</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Trade-offs</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Auto-tracking via ref.watch(), rich provider type system, code generation support, ProviderScope for testing, dominant Flutter solution</li>
    <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Flutter-only, push propagation means glitch concerns apply, ProviderScope boilerplate, migration from Provider can be significant</li>
  </ul>

  <hr />

  <h2>Other Flutter State Solutions</h2>

  <h3>Provider (Legacy)</h3>
  <p>Provider wraps Flutter's <code>InheritedWidget</code> with a simpler API. It is push-based with no dependency graph &mdash; state changes are broadcast via <code>notifyListeners()</code>:</p>
  <Code code={providerLegacyCode} lang="dart" />
  <p>Provider remains widely used but lacks compile-time safety and graph-based dependency tracking. Riverpod was created by the same author to address these limitations.</p>

  <h3>BLoC</h3>
  <p>BLoC (Business Logic Component) uses an event-driven, stream-based pattern. It enforces strict separation between UI and business logic:</p>
  <Code code={blocCode} lang="dart" />
  <p>BLoC is push-based with no dependency graph. It excels at event-driven architectures but requires significant boilerplate compared to Riverpod.</p>

  <h3>GetX</h3>
  <p>GetX provides reactive state, navigation, and dependency injection in a single package. While popular, it mixes concerns and uses a global mutable state approach that diverges from Flutter's compositional philosophy.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2>How Flutter Compares to Other Platforms</h2>

  <p>Flutter's state management landscape most closely resembles <strong>iOS</strong> in terms of diversity and maturity. Both platforms have multiple competing approaches spanning push-based and graph-based paradigms.</p>

